summary: Shares of Cisco Systems (CSCO) are up 14 cents, or 0.4% at $34.39, after the company announced it will buy telecom software provider Broadsoft (BSFT) for $55 per share in cash, for an aggregate purchase price of $1.9 billion, net of cash, at almost no premium to the $53.90 at which Broadsoft closed on Friday.  The price, the companies noted, is, however, at a 28% premium to the "unaffected" closing price of BroadSoft back on August 29th, before rumors circulated of a deal.  Cisco’s Rob Salvagno  explained in a blog post that Cisco desires Broadsoft’s “cloud collaboration platforms, which strengthen our cloud investments and ability to deliver collaboration solutions." If you want more background on Broadsoft, you could consider reading a post on Friday that discussed positive remarks about the importance of the company on the part of Dmitry Netis of William Blair, who suggested that Amazon (AMZN) should buy them.

Cisco's commentary on public sector improvements, particularly from the federal government, is reassuring, he argues, but budget uncertainty is still an issue, which could affect resellers like CDW (CDW), Insight Enterprises (NSIT), ePlus (PLUS), and IT distributors like Arrow Electronics (ARW), Tech Data (TECD) and Synnex (SNX) with public exposure.

summary: Following a report this afternoon of better-than-expected fiscal Q4 revenue from networking giant Cisco Systems (CSCO), the company’s management held a conference call with analysts, a noteworthy item of which was the announcement it will change its financial reporting of product revenue each quarter.  Chief financial officer Kelly Kramer said the company will begin describing its revenue according to the categories “infrastructure platform, applications, security, services and other.” Kramer said the new reporting categories will "better align with our evolving business model." Among the details of last quarter’s report, Cisco’s switching sales, 28% of its revenue, fell 9%, year over year, which will fuel concerns of the bears that the company continues to lose share to Arista Networks (ANET) and Juniper Networks (JNPR).
title: Cisco to Change Reporting Into Five Categories to 'Better Align with Evolving Biz Model'

summary: Networking giant Cisco Systems (CSCO) this afternoon reported  fiscal Q4 revenue a little bit better than analysts’ had projected, and met expectations, with its earnings per share, and forecast revenue to decline this quarter slightly less than consensus, sending its shares down slightly in late trading.  EPS is seen in a range of 59 cents to 61 cents, on a non-GAAP basis, in line with consensus for 60 cents.  CEO Chuck Robbins called it “another strong quarter” to cap off “a transformative year.” Added Robbins, "We made tremendous progress transitioning our business to more software and recurring revenue and delivered on our commitment to accelerate innovation in our core and across the portfolio." "The network has never been more critical to business success and we are building the network of the future." Details on individual product categories will likely come in the company’s conference call with analysts, starting at 4:30 pm, Eastern time, this evening.

summary: Shares of networker Arista Networks (ANET) are up $29.41, or 20%, at $173.46, extending last night’s gains, after it reported Q2 sales of networking gear that easily beat Wall Street expectations, and offered an outlook for this quarter's revenue that also came in well ahead.  The shares have gotten at least two upgrades today, along with several price target increases.  J.P. Morgan’s Rod Hall raises his rating on the shares to Overweight, and raises his price target to $186 from $144, writing that “sometimes expensive things are that way for a reason and we believe this is the case for Arista." Hall notes the company’s speed up in revenue growth, to 51% from 39%, and that Arista has repeatedly beaten his own estimates even while fighting a legal battle with Cisco Systems (CSCO) — a battle "now largely in the rearview mirror with patents in the latest case being declared invalid by PTAB." "It is hard to overstate how well this team continues to execute in our opinion,” he writes.

Broadcom supplies Cisco, and Brocade competes with Cisco, in  making fiber channel switches that transfer large amounts of  data between servers and other devices, the FTC said.

summary: WASHINGTON/MOSCOW (Reuters) - Western technology companies, including Cisco (CSCO.O), IBM (IBM.N) and SAP (SAPG.DE), are acceding to demands by Moscow for access to closely guarded product security secrets, at a time when Russia has been accused of a growing number of cyber attacks on the West, a Reuters investigation has found.  Russian authorities are asking Western tech companies to allow them to review source code for security products such as firewalls, anti-virus applications and software containing encryption before permitting the products to be imported and sold in the country.  While a number of U.S. firms say they are playing ball to preserve their entree to Russia's huge tech market, at least one U.S. firm, Symantec (SYMC.O), told Reuters it has stopped cooperating with the source code reviews over security concerns.
title: Under pressure, Western tech firms bow to Russian demands to share cyber secrets

summary: Shares of Cisco Systems (CSCO) are down 16 cents, or half a percent, at $31.69, after the company yesterday held an event at The Pearl event space in San Francisco to unveil some new networking products and technologies that it said will help companies manage the ever-rising plethora of devices while providing greater network security.  Another critical piece of the announcement is that many capabilities can be had without buying all-new hardware, but instead by taking a software subscription license, for 3, 5 or 7 years in duration.  There seems to be much positive reception today to the announcements. Even the bears found something to appreciate. J.P. Morgan’s Rod Hall reiterates a Neutral rating, writing that he had expected any update of the company’s “campus” switching gear — the Catalyst models — and so "this is a positive development in our opinion." "We also see the addition of encrypted traffic analysis as interesting and potentially differentiating for Cisco." Cisco’s event was the same day that arch rival Arista Networks (ANET) announced new offerings in its data center switches and routers, which means someone crashed someone else's party.
title: Cisco: Street Pleased with 'Intuitive' Network, New Software Offering

summary: Networker Arista Networks (ANET) got another piece of good news today in its legal battle with competitor Cisco Systems (CSCO), with the International Trade Commission saying that products that have been “redesigned” by Arista will meet the requirements of a “cease and desist order” the ITC imposed.  Today’s ruling follows the company having been granted a favorable ruling in the other ITC case, the so-called ‘945 case, a little over two weeks ago, which, at the time, Needham & Co. analyst Alex Henderson said basically “cleared the decks” for Arista as far as the main outstanding claims against it by Cisco.  Arista said in a press release that the ITC found its redesigned products meet the requirements for the so-called ‘944 case, one of multiple suits that Cisco brought against Arista back in 2014 for allegedly infringing multiple Cisco patents.
title: Arista Rising: Notches Another Win in Cisco Affair at ITC

summary: Shares of networking equipment vendor Arista Networks (ANET) today closed up $3.74, or 2.5%, at $152.26, after the U.S Patent and Trademark Office’s Patent Trial and Appeal Board yesterday issued a decision finding for Arista’s claims that another of Cisco Systems (CSCO) patents over which Cisco was suing Arista is “unpatentable." It is the second time in a week the company received a favorable judgment from the Patent board, the prior one having been from the same case.  The PTAB decision confirms a report yesterday by Wells Fargo’s Jess Lubert in which he related the decision.  In its write-up, the Patent board stated, “We determine that Petitioner has met its burden of showing, by a preponderance of the evidence, that all of the claims for which trial was instituted are unpatentable.” The “Petitioner” in this case is Arista.

summary: Here are some things going on today in your world of tech: Shares of networker Arista Networks (ANET) are down $1.45, or 1%, at $146.61, despite price targets rising this morning after word circulated yesterday afternoon that the company won a patent victory against Cisco Systems (CSCO).  After Wells Fargo claimed Arista got a favorable ruling from the Patent and Trademark Association, the association today confirmed that fact, with a posting from the administrative patent judges who said that Cisco’s approach to “maintain a set of access control patterns” is “unpatentable," as Arista claimed.  The final judgement, chock full of networking diagrams, concludes Cisco’s technology "would have been obvious … to a person of ordinary skill in the art." In response to all that, Gabelli & Co.’s Hendi Susanto thinks this is an "incremental positive” and reiterates a Buy rating, while Credit Suisse’s Kulbinder Garcha thinks that nonetheless, the upside for the company is “priced in” to the shares and reiterates a Neutral rating and a $140 price target.

Multinational companies with research centers far from their home countries don’t always see significant payoffs from their investment because businesses lack efficient ways to fund innovative projects at those facilities, says Prithwiraj “Raj” Choudhury, an assistant professor at Harvard Business School who conducted the research.  “Distant inventors lose out because they are not face to face at the right time with corporate decision makers,” Mr. Choudhury explains.
title: One Trick for Getting Bosses to Buy In to Your Idea

CEO Chuck Robbins said he was "pleased with the progress we are making on the multi-year transformation of our business."  CFO Kelly Kramer said the company had "executed well" in the quarter, with "solid profitability and cash generation." Added Kramer, "We will continue to invest in growth areas as we move the business toward more software and recurring revenue and return value to shareholders."  Gross profit margin decline to 63.2% for products, from 64.5% in the prior-year period.

Symantec and Kaspersky Lab said on Monday that some  code in an earlier version of the WannaCry software had also  appeared in programs used by the Lazarus Group, which  researchers from many companies have identified as a North  Korea-run hacking operation.  "This is the best clue we have seen to date as to the  origins of WannaCry," Kaspersky Lab researcher Kurt Baumgartner  told Reuters.
title: Researchers see possible North Korea link to global cyber attack

summary: Major U.S. multinationals are  pushing the Trump administration to deepen the tax break it has  already tentatively proposed on $2.6 trillion in corporate  profits being held offshore, a key piece in Washington's  intricate tax reform puzzle.  As President Donald Trump tries to deliver on his campaign  promise to overhaul the tax code, lobbyists for technology, drug  and other manufacturers are working with officials behind closed  doors, six lobbyists working with various industries told  Reuters.  In line with tax cuts already embraced by Republicans in the  House of Representatives, the lobbyists said they are telling  the White House and Treasury Department that if companies are  forced to bring home, or repatriate, foreign earnings, they want  a sharply reduced tax rate.

summary: Shares of Cisco Systems (CSCO) are down 25 cents, or 0.8%, at $34.04, after BMO Capital’s Tim Long this morning cut his rating on the shares to Market Perform from Outperform, and trimmed his price target to $35 from $37, writing that the company’s “transformation” from an equipment vendor to a vendor of software and services predominantly will “take many years,” keeping the stock in a “trading range." The company’s “recurring revenue” from products may grow from 10% now to 16% at the end of fiscal 2018, he opines, but because routing and switching, Cisco’s biggest lines of business, won’t move to the software and services model “anytime soon,” they are a headwind to greater progress.  "We believe some of the challenges Cisco faces will stay in focus until recurring revenues are bigger,” writes Long.
title: Cisco's Transformation Will Take Years, Says BMO

summary: Shares of networker Arista Networks (ANET), which competes with Cisco Systems (CSCO) and Juniper Networks (JNPR), closed up $4.52, or 3%, at $144.72, bouncing back from a weak open, after the company yesterday reported Q1 results that easily beat expectations, and forecast this quarter’s results higher as well.  Price targets are rising today at several shops, though the shares may be somewhat held back by the fact that Cisco Systems (CSCO) posted a blog post yesterday saying the International Trade Commission found two more violations of Cisco patents on the part of Arista.  Arista responded with a statement from its general counsel, Marc Taxay, stating "We once again appreciate the tireless work of the Commission in completing this investigation and finding that we did not infringe 4 out of the 6 patents,” and vowing, "We intend to address the infringement allegations with redesigns for our products in full compliance with the orders." That’s doesn’t allay everyone’s fears. MKM Partners’s Michael Genovese reiterates a Neutral rating, though he hiked his price target to $125 from $100, writing that the report was “solid,” and there were several “positives,” including steady business with its largest customers, a partnership with Hewlett Packard Enterprise (HPE), and its new software approach to networking.
title: Arista Rises: Amidst Cisco Litigation, Is Upside Priced In?

summary: Shares of International Business Machines (IBM) are down $4.51, or almost 3%, at $154.54, after Berkshire Hathaway’s Warren Buffett told Becky Quick of CNBC last night that he has sold a third of his holdings in the stock.  Asked if he’s going to sell more, he waffled a bit: "I don’t think we’ll be selling, in fact, we could buy,” but, "They’ve run into some very tough competition.” Buffett said IBM CEO Ginni Rometty "was out some weeks ago” to talk with Buffett about the matter after learning of his share sale through a private “stock watch” firm that Buffett seemed intrigued was able to spy on his selling pattern.  Among Street responses, Maynard Um of Wells Fargo, who has a Market Perform rating on the shares, writes this morning, "shares will be rangebound, exacerbated by the influence of Mr. Buffett’s comments, particularly around competition,” and that “we believe IBM will have to show fundamental improvement in order to see multiple expansion though think 2017 will be another transition year." Shares of networker Arista Networks (ANET) are down 85 cents, or 0.6%, at $139.31, giving up last night’s after-hours gains, after the company easily beat Q1 expectations for revenue and profit, and forecast this quarter’s results higher as well.
title: Tech Today: Buffett Dumps IBM, OLED Soars, Arista, AAOI Rising

summary: Shares of Cisco Systems (CSCO) are up 34 cents, or 1%, at $33.74, after Credit Suisse’s Kulbinder Garcha today raised his rating on the shares to Outperform from Underperform, and raised his price target to $40 from $27, arguing that tit can make some meaningful acquisitions, possibly Splunk (SPLK), ServiceNow (NOW), and Palo Alto Networks (PANW), and that it’s earnings can grow, despite challenges in its switching equipment business, the largest single chunk of Cisco’s revenue.  All in all, he’s come to believe in the “transformation”Cisco has articulated to the Street.  "At the heart of our change of view,” writes Garcha, "is that the company is embarking on a successful transformation that diversifies the business away from switching, becoming a more diversified IT player with a higher recurring element of software offerings." Garcha notes Cisco has shifted “away from networking”:  Networking represented 83% of revenues in year 2000 and 53% in 2010, but now stands at 45% today.
title: Cisco: Credit Suisse Ups to Buy from Sell as It 'Transforms'

Senior Cisco managers immediately reassigned staff from  other projects to figure out how the CIA hacking tricks worked,  so they could help customers patch their systems and prevent  criminal hackers or spies from using the same methods, three  employees told Reuters on condition of anonymity.

summary: [Reuters] - When WikiLeaks founder Julian Assange disclosed earlier this month that his anti-secrecy group had obtained CIA tools for hacking into technology products made by U.S. companies, security engineers at Cisco Systems (CSCO.O) swung into action. The Wikileaks documents described how the Central Intelligence Agency had learned more than a year ago how to exploit flaws in Cisco's widely used Internet switches, which direct electronic traffic, to enable eavesdropping. Senior Cisco managers immediately reassigned staff from other projects to figure out how the CIA hacking tricks worked, so they could help customers patch their systems and prevent criminal hackers or spies from using the same methods, three employees told Reuters on condition of anonymity.
title: A scramble at Cisco exposes uncomfortable truths about U.S. cyber defense

The officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity, told Reuters that they believed documents published by WikiLeaks on Tuesday about CIA techniques used between 2013 and 2016 were authentic. The documents showed that CIA hackers could get into Apple Inc (AAPL.O) iPhones, Google Inc (GOOGL.O) Android devices and other gadgets in order to capture text and voice messages before they were encrypted with sophisticated software.

Cisco said its deferred revenue, a measure of the company's move to being more of a software-driven firm, rose 13%, year over year, to $17.1 billion, and said deferred revenue from products, specifically, was up 19%, "driven largely by subscription-based and software offerings." Cisco added that the "portion of product deferred revenue related to recurring software and subscription businesses grew 51%." For the April-ending quarter, the company sees revenue in a range of flat to down 2%, from the prior-year period.

The group, which also includes Bank of New York Mellon Corp (BK.N), Foxconn Technology Group, security company Gemalto and blockchain startups Consensus Systems (ConsenSys), BitSE and Chronicled Inc said on Friday that they will collaborate to develop a shared blockchain protocol for the internet of things - the concept that everyday objects, from washing machines to shipping containers, will be connected to the internet and will be able to send and receive data.

summary: [at Barrons.com] - Things start to get really hard for traditional enterprise computing vendors in 2017, writes J.P. Morgan’s Rod Hall today in a note to clients, warning that spending for “on-premise” IT stuff will begin to decline as public cloud computing takes over. Hall thinks the reduced spending, as Amazon.com (AMZN) and the cloud vendors gobble up compute cycles, could hurt Cisco Systems (CSCO) and other traditional IT vendors. "While we are currently predicting a very small 2% decline we would expect the deterioration to accelerate and begin to materially affect Cisco and other legacy vendors by 2018." Cloud computing is growing fast, with cloud revenue rising 60% this year, to $19 billion, though it only makes up 8% of total data center IT spending of $222 billion, he estimates.
title: Cisco's In For a Rough Time as Public Cloud Takes Over, Says JP Morgan

summary: IBM sees tipping point at hand for industrial Internet
title: IBM sees tipping point at hand for industrial Internet

summary: [Reuters] - Plugging computer sensors into factories, cars, shops and offices to help them operate more smartly on the industrial Internet, or so-called Internet of Things (IoT), is moving beyond prototypes into the mass market, IBM said on Monday. The computer services and software company, which has struggled with flagging growth in its traditional business in recent years, said its industrial Internet business has surged to 6,000 paying customers from 4,000 at the end of 2015. The IoT, which gives many billions of machine parts the capability to send and receive data, is vital to IBM's (IBM.N) turnaround as it has refocused on areas that promise profitable growth such as analytics, security and cloud services.
title: IBM sees tipping point at hand for industrial Internet

summary: [at Barrons.com] - Networking giant Cisco Systems (CSCO) has wrapped up its earnings conference call, following a report of better-than-expected fiscal Q4 results, and an in-line forecast, a call that fielded a bunch of questions about two big unknowns: how to understand the company’s 5,500 person layoff announcement, and how to understand what seems to be a bottomless outlook for the telecom equipment market. CEO Chuck Robbins and CFO Kelley Kramer were kind enough to talk with me by phone following the call. Cisco had said in its press release that it was seeking to "optimize" itself to compete in "key priority areas such as security, IoT, collaboration, next generation data center and cloud." Kramer told me that while the company is “never happy” about having to let someone go, “we are going to be agile about taking advantage of where there’s growth and where there’s not." I asked Robbins about that statement.
title: Cisco's CEO Robbins on Layoffs: 'I Would Like to See That Be the Exception'

summary: [Reuters] - Cisco Systems Inc said it would cut nearly 7 percent of its workforce, posting charges of up to $400 million in its first quarter, as the world's largest networking gear maker shifts focus from its legacy hardware towards higher-margin software. The gradual move to fast-growing sectors such as security, the Internet of Things and the cloud is a response to sluggish demand for Cisco's traditional lineup of switches and routers from telecom carriers and enterprise customers, amid intense competition from companies such as Huawei and Juniper Networks Inc. Savings from up to 5,500 job cuts would be reinvested into key growth areas, Cisco said.
